        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Architecture Overview of FLUX.2 Klein 4B BF16"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The FLUX.2 Klein 4B BF16 model is a compact variant designed for inference efficiency, leveraging bfloat16 (BF16) precision to reduce memory bandwidth and accelerate computations on modern hardware. Key architectural features include a 4-billion parameter count optimized for edge and cloud deployments, with support for dynamic batching and kernel optimizations. Understanding these elements helps teams align infrastructure with model capabilities to baseline latency expectations."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Key Factors Affecting FLUX.2 Klein 4B BF16 Latency"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "p",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Several factors directly impact FLUX.2 Klein 4B BF16 latency in API setups. Hardware choices, such as GPU type (e.g., NVIDIA A100 vs. T4), influence parallel processing speeds, while software stack configurations—including driver versions, CUDA libraries, and runtime frameworks like ONNX Runtime or TensorRT—can introduce overhead. Network latency between clients and servers, batch size selection, and concurrent request handling also play critical roles. For instance, improper batch sizing may lead to underutilized resources or increased queueing delays, so profiling these variables is crucial for pinpointing bottlenecks."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "h2",
        "children": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Optimization Strategies for Latency Reduction"
